.TH MYDATE "1" "December 2025" "mydate 202208131841-git" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
mydate \- Display date, time, and version information
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B mydate
[\fI\,OPTIONS\/\fR] [\fI\,COMMAND\/\fR] [\fI\,FORMAT\/\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B mydate
is a utility script for displaying date, time, and version information in various formats. It provides convenient commands for getting timestamps suitable for versioning files and projects.
.PP
The script supports custom date formats and can write version strings directly to files.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B nowtime
Display the current time
.TP
.B nowdate
Display the current date
.TP
.B setver
Display the current version timestamp (YYYYMMDDHHMM-git format)
.TP
.B setverfile \fI\,FILE\/\fR
Write the version timestamp to the specified file
.TP
.B custom \fI\,FORMAT\/\fR
Display date/time using a custom format string
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-\-file " " \fI\,FILE\/\fR
Set the output file name
.TP
.BR \-\-dir " " \fI\,DIRECTORY\/\fR
Set the working directory
.TP
.BR \-\-help
Display help message with usage information and available commands
.TP
.BR \-\-config
Generate or regenerate user configuration file with default settings
.TP
.BR \-\-version
Show script version information and exit
.TP
.BR \-\-options
Display all available command-line options
.TP
.BR \-\-debug
Enable debug mode with verbose output and command tracing (set -x)
.TP
.BR \-\-raw
Disable colorized output for plain text display
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B mydate
Display date, time, and version information
.TP
.B mydate nowtime
Show the current time
.TP
.B mydate nowdate
Show the current date
.TP
.B mydate setver
Display version timestamp (e.g., 202312151430-git)
.TP
.B mydate setverfile version.txt
Write version timestamp to version.txt
.TP
.B mydate custom "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"
Display date/time in custom format
.SH FILES
.TP
.B ~/.config/myscripts/mydate/settings.conf
User configuration file for mydate preferences
.TP
.B ~/.local/log/mydate/
Log file directory for error tracking
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success
.TP
.B 1
General error
